  "datePublished": "2026-03-21",
  "description": "A Polity is a quadruple (T_P, J_P, Aut, C_P) — a constitutional theory T_P (a geometric theory classifying valid institutional forms), a recognition topology J_P (the Grothendieck topology grounding collective recognition within the polity), an autarkeia certificate Aut (the polity is self-sufficient: its classifying topos [T_P] has a conservative set of points — every institutional question within the polity is decided by some model of T_P), and a constituent power C_P (the founding act that constitutes T_P without itself deriving authority from any prior T). The defining structure: the polity is the entity that grants flags to ships, issues the authorizing act A that makes charters binding, and provides the background topology within which all institutions within it acquire constitutional force. Mathematical correspondence: the polity is the classifying topos [T_P] = Sh(Site(T_P), J_T) for the geometric theory T_P — every institution within the polity is a model of T_P, hence a geometric morphism from the institution's topos into [T_P]. Aristotle's autarkes (self-sufficient community, Politics I.2, 1253a2): the polity is the level at which the community is complete — it contains family, civil society, and the legal order as articulated members, and does not require appeal to a higher community for its internal legitimacy.",
  "name": "Polity",
